<br>
Michael,<br>
    My heart goes out to you...I have not experienced PTSD myself, but I'm in a <br>
relationship with a vet who has and work <br>
with people in the throws of this <br>
nightmare.  Your description of your <br>
feelings fit that profile to the &quot;T&quot;.<br><br>
There are some wonderful men on these <br>
pages who have experienced the same thing and would welcome you with open arms and <br>
would have more credible advice than I. <br><br>
But here are my thoughts: I can say that you MUST start by being <br>
kind to yourself - PTSD is an entirely <br>
normal reaction to abnormal experiences, <br>
but &quot;you&quot; are not your symptoms.  You are having this reaction because you are a <br>
feeling, compassionate human (even though some of your ways of behaving may make <br>
you think otherwise) - embrace your own <br>
heart with all of its pain.  I would <br>
guess that praying was effective when the symptoms were milder...it's harder to <br>
turn things over to God when we really <br>
hit the deep stuff, because we <br>
instinctively feel the need to control <br>
things when our lives are spinning out of control. That seems to be the catch 22, <br>
because the &quot;phone lines&quot; to <br>
God/spirit/unconditional love open up <br>
only when we are willing to let go of our will - on the otherhand it is your <br>
indominable will that has kept you going. Quite a balancing act.<br><br>
I'm sure that this is hard to see right <br>
now, but &quot;our greatest gifts sometimes <br>
come in the strangest packages.&quot;  Embrace the pain, the memories, and the &quot;cold <br>
wind.&quot;  The only way out of the woods is <br>
&quot;through it.&quot;  Everytime you try to go <br>
around it (via numbing out), you'll <br>
simply end up here again, with the same <br>
dark shadows lurking.  I know first hand <br>
that riding this storm will be one of the shakiest of your life, but when you come <br>
out the other side you will be amazed at <br>
how many pieces fall in place, once <br>
you've looked the &quot;monster in the eye.&quot; <br>
 Don't judge yourself, simply because <br>
others have not understood your behavior <br>
(few people are educated on this) and may not have been supportive.  Learn to <br>
observe your mind as seperate from your <br>
heart and ignore its urgings to run away <br>
or shut down - your heart is crying out <br>
for healing.  If you have anyone in your <br>
life that has shown compassion or <br>
understanding, go through this with them.  Talk, talk, talk and cry with them.  The hardest thing to do is set aside your <br>
pride and inability to trust - it takes <br>
real guts, but the rewards are <br>
innumerable.  If there really is no one, <br>
schedule your appointments closer <br>
together with your counselor - it is <br>
imperative that you get support through <br>
this process.    If possible take some time off work so that you won't have to worry <br>
about losing control in the wrong place.<br>
Be patient with yourself, but KNOW that <br>
you can and will make it.<br><br>
Everyone has their own way &quot;home&quot;, but if any of these thoughts spark a recognition of truth in you, then perhaps that may be your way back.  There are many, many <br>
different &quot;roads&quot; offered on these pages <br>
- have faith that one of them will be <br>
yours.  You will find several &quot;squad buddies&quot; on these pages, talk to them, they have been amazingly determined and effective at helping eachother heal.<br><br>
If you need to talk some more, please <br>
feel free to e-mail me, I would be <br>
honored to listen.  God bless you <br>
Michael, remember those who have taken <br>
the painful road in life have the <br>
greatest gifts to offer when &quot;they come <br>
out the other side.&quot;  There are many here who care deeply and are looking forward <br>
to welcoming you home.
